&lt;p&gt;I was recently asked about the headache of re-writing things in my Bullet Journal. I have an interesting trick in fixing that. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;I do the task so I don&#39;t have to write it down more than once or twice.&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I have to write it down more than twice, I must convince myself that is a task worth keeping. I do this by looking at how long a task will take. If less than 30 minutes, I do it on the spot.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This idea is like that of a Mitch Hedberg joke.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;I sit in a hotel and think of something funny. When I think of something,  I get a pen and pad and write it down. If I can&#39;t find a pen or pad, I convince myself that what I just thought of was not that funny&lt;sup class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; id=&#34;fnref-1&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn-1&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I often convince myself to do the thing instead of writing it down for the umpteenth-time. Alternatively, I strike it and say, &#34;This isn&#39;t important&#34;.&lt;/p&gt;

